1. JSON-LD Core Concepts
- JSON-LD serializes Linked Data in JSON. Documents are JSON objects that map keys to IRIs via a context (@context).
- Identifiers: node identifiers use @id and must be IRIs or blank node identifiers. Use absolute or relative IRIs; relative IRIs are resolved against base IRI.
- Types: use @type to assign RDF types (IRIs) to nodes. Multiple types are allowed as arrays.
- Values: value objects may include @value, @type, @language, and @direction. Typed values use XML Schema datatypes (xsd:dateTime, xsd:integer, etc.).
- Graphs: use @graph to contain multiple node objects representing an RDF graph. Named graphs use graph containers and dataset constructs.
- Node objects: JSON objects representing nodes must follow node-object grammar; properties map to IRIs via term definitions or compact IRIs.

2. JSON-LD Processing Forms and Algorithms
- Processing algorithms: expand, compact, frame, flatten, flattening, toRDF, fromRDF, normalize (URDNA2015), merge, and framing algorithm.
- expand(input, options): produces the expanded form where all terms resolved to absolute IRIs; keywords preserved; values normalized into value objects.
- compact(input, context, options): uses supplied @context to shorten IRIs into terms or compact IRIs, performs type coercion per context definitions.
- frame(input, frame, options): restructures data to match a frame (template) producing nested results and ordering defined by frame semantics.
- flatten(input, context?, options): produces an array of node objects where each node has a distinct @id; useful for deterministic iteration and graph manipulation.
- toRDF(input, options): maps JSON-LD to an RDF dataset (quads) following the RDF conversion rules (IRIs, literals, blank nodes, graphs).
- fromRDF(dataset, options): converts RDF datasets (N-Quads style) back to JSON-LD structures; requires mapping rules for datatype/language detection.
- normalize(input, options): canonicalizes RDF dataset using URDNA2015 (or URGNA2012) to produce a deterministic normalized N-Quads string for signing or comparison.

3. Contexts and Term Definitions
- @context may be an object, array, or IRI. A context maps terms to IRIs and can include:
  - term definition components: @id (IRI or compact IRI), @type (IRI or "@id"/"@vocab" for coercion), @container (none, @list, @set, @index, @language, @graph), @language default, @reverse, @context (scoped contexts), @protected, @prefix boolean.
  - @vocab defines a default vocabulary IRI to prepend to terms without a colon or absolute IRI.
  - @base defines base IRI for relative IRI resolution.
  - Context import: contexts may reference remote contexts via an IRI; processors load and merge term maps following import rules and scoping.
- Compact IRIs: prefix:suffix forms are expanded by mapping prefix to IRI in context; if prefix maps to @vocab or IRI, expand to prefix+suffix.
- Scoped contexts: term definitions may include nested @context to apply only when the term is used as an object value.
- Protected terms: term definitions with @protected true prevent overriding by later context merges.

4. JSON-LD Keywords and Containers
- Keywords: @context, @id, @type, @value, @language, @list, @set, @graph, @included, @reverse, @index, @container, @vocab, @base, @protected, @nest.
- Container types supported in term definitions: @list, @set, @index, @language, @graph, @id, @type; choose container to control representation shape in compacted form.
- @reverse: used to express reverse properties; the value is an object mapping properties to values which point back to the subject.
- @included: include external nodes that are to be merged into main graph without renaming.

5. Forms: Expanded, Compacted, Flattened, Framed
- Expanded form: every term replaced with full IRI keys; values are normalized as arrays and value objects; no context present.
- Compacted form: user-supplied context shortens IRIs to terms; single-valued properties may be represented as scalars per context coercion; ordering not guaranteed.
- Flattened form: single array of node objects each with unique @id; graph structure preserved via @graph references; useful for bulk processing.
- Framed form: the result of applying a frame template; can include default values, require presence of properties, and produce nested structures matching application schema.

6. JSON-LD and RDF Interop
- Mapping rules: JSON-LD provides a precise Mapping to RDF Graphs: node objects map to RDF subjects, properties to predicates (IRIs), values to objects (IRIs or literals with datatype/language), graphs to named graphs.
- RDF serializations: JSON-LD can be losslessly converted to RDF and vice versa when JSON-LD uses RDF-compatible constructs; blank nodes are preserved via generated identifiers.
- Data typing: JSON-LD maps typed values to xsd datatypes; language maps to rdf:langString (or named string with language) per RDF 1.1.

7. RDF Data Model
- Triples: statements of form subject predicate object. Subject: IRI or blank node; predicate: IRI; object: IRI, literal, or blank node.
- IRIs: internationalized identifiers; may appear in all triple positions; relative IRIs resolved against base.
- Literals: typed with datatypes (xsd:string, xsd:boolean, xsd:dateTime, xsd:integer); may have language tags (@lang).
- Blank nodes: anonymous nodes used when no global IRI is available; appear in subject or object positions; serializations may assign internal labels (_:b0).
- Datasets: collections of multiple graphs (default graph plus named graphs) used in SPARQL and RDF datasets (N-Quads representation).

8. RDF Serializations
- Turtle: compact, human-readable RDF syntax using prefixes and triples terminated by dots.
- N-Triples: line-based plain serialization of triples; one triple per line; suitable for streaming and diffing.
- N-Quads / TriG: N-Quads extends N-Triples with graph name (for datasets); TriG is a Turtle-like syntax for datasets.
- RDF/XML: XML serialization; required minimal support by OWL 2 tools for interchange.
- JSON-LD: JSON-based RDF serialization; use @context to control compacting and term mapping; toRDF/fromRDF algorithms define mapping.

9. OWL 2: Structure, Syntaxes, Semantics, Profiles
- Ontology elements: classes, properties (object/data), individuals, datatype values, axioms (subClassOf, equivalentClass, disjointWith, property characteristics).
- Syntaxes: RDF/XML (mandatory), OWL/XML, Functional-Style Syntax, Manchester Syntax, Turtle (optional). RDF/XML must be supported for interchange; other syntaxes optional.
- Semantics: Direct Semantics (mapping to SROIQ description logic; used for OWL 2 DL reasoning) and RDF-Based Semantics (assigns meaning to RDF graphs; allows OWL 2 Full).
- Profiles: OWL 2 EL (polynomial-time reasoning; large ontologies), OWL 2 QL (conjunctive query rewriting to SQL; suitable for databases), OWL 2 RL (rule-based, RDF triple-oriented; polynomial implementations, may be incomplete).
- Mapping to RDF: OWL structural forms map to RDF graphs via a specified Mapping to RDF Graphs; ensure syntactic constraints for OWL 2 DL (e.g., transitive properties in number restrictions constraints).

10. Schema.org Markup
- Embedding options: Microdata attributes (itemscope, itemtype, itemprop), RDFa attributes, or JSON-LD script elements (type="application/ld+json").
- Microdata patterns: itemscope declares the item, itemtype points to type IRI (e.g., https://schema.org/Movie), itemprop names properties; nested items use nested itemscope with itemprop.
- JSON-LD embedding: place a script tag with type application/ld+json containing a JSON-LD document; inherit base IRI from HTML base element; respect script element restrictions.
- Dates/times: use time element with datetime attribute in ISO 8601 format for unambiguous date/time values (YYYY-MM-DD or combined dateTime).
- Enumerations: use link or explicit schema.org enumeration IRIs (e.g., https://schema.org/InStock) via link href to unambiguously identify enumeration values.

11. jsonld (npm) API Reference (Node/JavaScript)
- Core async API methods and signatures (Promise-based):
  - expand(input[, options]) -> Promise<expandedDoc>
    - input: JSON-LD document or object
    - options: { base: string, documentLoader: fn, expandContext: object|IRI, processingMode: string }
    - returns: expanded JSON-LD (arrays, fully expanded IRIs)
  - compact(input, context[, options]) -> Promise<compactedDoc>
    - context: context object or IRI
    - options: { base, documentLoader, expandContext, processingMode, compactToRelative }
  - flatten(input[, contextOrOptions]) -> Promise<flattenedDoc>
  - frame(input, frame[, options]) -> Promise<framedDoc>
  - toRDF(input[, options]) -> Promise<rdfDataset>
    - options: { format: 'application/n-quads' | 'internal', produceGeneralizedRdf: boolean }
    - returns: RDF dataset (N-Quads string or internal dataset object)
  - fromRDF(dataset[, options]) -> Promise<jsonldDoc>
    - dataset: N-Quads string or dataset object
    - options: { expandContext, useRdfType }
  - normalize(input[, options]) -> Promise<normalizedNQuads>
    - options: { algorithm: 'URDNA2015'|'URGNA2012', format: 'application/n-quads' }
  - documentLoader(url) -> Promise{document}
    - pluggable loader used by processors to fetch contexts and remote documents; must return { contextUrl, documentUrl, document }.
- Error handling: methods reject Promises with Error objects detailing misuse (invalid context, unknown keywords, I/O failures in loaders).
- Implementation patterns: chain operations: jsonld.expand(doc).then(exp => jsonld.flatten(exp)).then(flat => jsonld.compact(flat, ctx)). Use async/await in modern Node.


SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS

JSON-LD Processing Modes
- processingMode option values: 'json-ld-1.1' (default for JSON-LD 1.1 processors), 'json-ld-1.0' for legacy behaviour; determines expansion/compaction rules (e.g., coercion, @language maps).

Context merging precedence
- Context application order: local contexts (within node object) override parent contexts; when merging arrays of contexts, later contexts overwrite earlier definitions unless @protected is set.

RDF Conversion specifics
- toRDF maps JSON-LD value objects to RDF literals: if value object has @type use that datatype; if has @language use rdf:langString; bare strings default to xsd:string or rdf:langString when language map used.
- IRIs in JSON-LD may use blank node identifiers with prefix _:; mapping to RDF uses same blank node labels if preserved; processors may rename during normalization.

OWL Practical Constraints
- For OWL 2 DL conformance avoid using RDF constructs that violate DL syntactic restrictions: do not use transitive properties in cardinality restrictions, and ensure property hierarchy and datatype usage follow OWL 2 DL structural spec.

Schema.org Microdata implementation specifics
- Use itemprop="url" on anchor elements when listing multiple items to map the listed item's canonical URL. Use link with itemprop and href for enumerations and canonical references.


